## PRINCIPLE DATABASE

Store:

### Pressure Principles

Examples:

• Liquidity expansion benefits risk assets.

• Yield expansion often pressures long-duration assets.

• Dollar strengthening often creates cross-asset headwinds.

• Sovereign refinancing stress can tighten liquidity conditions.

---

### Transmission Principles

Examples:

• Liquidity expansion does not always benefit expected assets immediately.

• Capital flows may be delayed.

• Multiple transmission pathways can exist simultaneously.

• Capital often moves toward the strongest beneficiary first.

---

### Environment Principles

Examples:

• Tier 1 environments produce the highest-quality opportunities.

• Poor liquidity environments reduce expectancy.

• High event-risk environments increase fragility.

• Stable participation improves continuation quality.

---

### Alignment Principles

Examples:

• Alignment scores above 8 consistently improve expectancy.

• Macro-chart conflict reduces probability.

• Alignment deterioration often precedes trade deterioration.

• Strong alignment improves follow-through quality.

---

### Execution Principles

Examples:

• Liquidity sweeps improve entry efficiency.

• Structure shifts improve directional confidence.

• High-quality FVGs improve asymmetry.

• Execution quality improves risk efficiency.

---

### Exposure Principles

Examples:

• Hidden concentration increases fragility.

• Diversification improves survivability.

• Correlated positions increase drawdown risk.

• Theme clustering often creates portfolio vulnerability.
• Carry expansion often supports risk assets.

• Carry contraction can reduce capital flow into risk assets.

• Carry unwind events can create cross-asset liquidation pressure.

• BOJ policy shifts can alter global funding conditions.

### Management Principles

Examples:

• Early profit protection preserves expectancy.

• Thesis deterioration should trigger reassessment.

• Structure failure often precedes larger deterioration.

• Effective management improves asymmetry.

---

